Appendix A – Material Specifications and Guaranteed Properties

All materials listed are commercially available and conform to the stated standards. Minimum guaranteed properties at 20 °C are used in all calculations. Safety factors (SF) are applied at system level as per Section 0.

A.1 Wrought Aluminium Alloys (Extrusions, Sheet)

Alloy/Temper Standard Form \sigma_y (MPa) \sigma_u (MPa) E (GPa) G (GPa) \nu Density (kg/m³)
6061‑T6 ASTM B221 Extruded 240 260 68.9 26.0 0.33 2700
6063‑T6 ASTM B221 Extruded 170 205 68.9 26.0 0.33 2700
6082‑T6 ASTM B221 Extruded 250 290 69.0 26.5 0.33 2700
5754‑H22 ASTM B209 Sheet 130 220 70.0 26.3 0.33 2660

Design values incorporate no knock‑down factors; safety factors are applied at system level.

A.2 Cast Aluminium Alloys

Alloy/Temper Process Standard \sigma_y (MPa) \sigma_u (MPa) E (GPa) Elongation (%) Density (kg/m³)
AlSi7Mg0,3‑T6 Vacuum die cast DIN EN 1706 160 220 72 5 2670
A356‑T6 Sand cast / permanent ASTM B26 160 220 72 5 2670
AlSi10Mg LPBF (as‑built, stress‑relieved) ASTM F3318 200 350 70 6 2670

Note: LPBF AlSi10Mg fatigue properties are not specified for primary structure; sand‑cast A356‑T6 is recommended for road‑going vehicles.

A.3 Carbon Fibre Reinforced Polymer (CFRP)

· Laminate architecture: [0/90/\pm45]_\text{s} quasi‑isotropic layup.
· Fibre: Toray T700S 12K, 60 % fibre volume fraction.
· Matrix: Epoxy resin, T_g = 120 °C.
· Thickness per ply: 0.20 mm.
· Cured ply properties (0° direction):

Property Symbol Value Unit
Longitudinal modulus E_1 121 GPa
Transverse modulus E_2 8.6 GPa
Shear modulus G_{12} 4.5 GPa
Poisson ratio \nu_{12} 0.30 –
Tensile strength (0°) X_t 1800 MPa
Compressive strength (0°) X_c 1000 MPa
In‑plane shear strength S 70 MPa

Design allowables: A‑basis (90 % confidence, 99 % reliability) knock‑down factor of 0.65 applied to all strength values.
Effective quasi‑isotropic modulus: E_{\text{eff}} = 70 GPa, G_{\text{eff}} = 4.5 GPa.

A.4 Structural Adhesives

Adhesive Type Cure condition \tau_{\text{ult}} (MPa) E_{\text{adh}} (MPa) Max service temp (°C)
SikaPower‑4980 Urethane 70 °C, 20 min 24 800 90
3M DP460 Epoxy 80 °C, 60 min 31 1700 120
Lord 410 Acrylic RT, 24 h 22 600 80

Design shear strength: \tau_{\text{design}} = \tau_{\text{ult}} / 2.0 (safety factor for environmental degradation, creep, and incomplete cure).

A.5 Fasteners (Steel)

Type Standard Material class \sigma_y (MPa) \sigma_u (MPa) Shear strength (MPa)
Hex bolt M12 ISO 4014 10.9 940 1040 600
Blind rivet 6.4 mm ISO 15977 Steel (Zn) – – 380 (single shear)

Design loads: Bolt proof load = 0.85 × \sigma_y × A_s; rivet design shear = 3.2 kN per rivet (SF 2.0 applied to ultimate).

---

Appendix B – Structural Joint Analysis: Adhesive + Mechanical Interlock

B.1 Track A – Casting‑to‑Battery Joint

Geometry:

· Adhesive bond width: 20 mm, length per side: 3200 mm → total area A_{\text{adh}} = 64\,000\ \text{mm}^2.
· Four taper pins per major casting: ø12 mm (minor) – ø14 mm (major), length 25 mm, stainless 17‑4PH H900 (\tau_y = 550 MPa, \sigma_y = 1100 MPa).
· Shear bosses: ø20 mm, height 5 mm, machined into CFRP skin with Al 6061‑T6 ring insert.

Load case – Longitudinal shear (frontal crash):

F_x = m_{\text{casting}} \cdot a_{\text{max}}

· Front lower crossmember mass = 7.5 kg, deceleration 40 g → F_x = 7.5 \cdot 40 \cdot 9.81 = 2943\ \text{N}.
· Adhesive shear stress \tau_{\text{adh}} = F_x / A_{\text{adh}} = 2943 / 64000 = 0.046\ \text{MPa} → negligible.
· Shear pins in double shear: capacity per pin = 2 \cdot (\pi \cdot 12^2 / 4) \cdot 550 / 1000 = 124.4\ \text{kN}. Four pins → 497.6 kN.
· Interlock dominates crash load path; adhesive provides stiffness, not ultimate strength.

Load case – Peeling moment (offset loading):

· Moment arm to adhesive centroid ~100 mm → M = F_x \cdot 0.1 = 294.3\ \text{Nm}.
· Peeling stress approximated by beam‑on‑elastic‑foundation model. With adhesive modulus E_{\text{adh}} = 800 MPa, bond thickness 0.5 mm, peel stress < 5 MPa → below design limit (12 MPa).
· Mechanical interlock: pins in tension (one side). Tensile capacity per pin: \pi \cdot 6^2 \cdot 1100 = 124.4\ \text{kN}. Four pins → 498 kN → far above required.

Redundancy condition: Even with 100 % adhesive失效, pins + bosses provide full crash load path. Shear bosses engage before 5 mm displacement.

B.2 Track B – Extrusion‑to‑Node Joint

Joint configuration:

· Epoxy adhesive (3M DP460), bond gap 0.2 mm, overlap length 50 mm, width 60 mm → A_{\text{adh}} = 3000\ \text{mm}^2 per joint.
· Blind rivets: 6.4 mm steel, 4 per joint, single shear capacity 3.2 kN each → total F_{\text{rivet,ult}} = 12.8\ \text{kN}.
· Combined stiffness: adhesive carries service loads; rivets provide fail‑safe.

Design limit:

· Adhesive ultimate load: \tau_{\text{ult}} \cdot A_{\text{adh}} = 31 \cdot 3000 = 93\ \text{kN}.
· Design governed by rivet capacity after adhesive failure: allowable per joint = 12.8 / 2.0 = 6.4\ \text{kN} (SF 2.0).

Rotational stiffness (detailed derivation in Appendix H):

K_\phi = \frac{M}{\theta} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{E A_i e_i^2}{L_i} + \frac{G_{\text{adh}} A_{\text{adh}} t_{\text{adh}}}{h}

Typical value for bonded‑riveted configuration: K_\phi \approx 8200\ \text{Nm/deg}.

---

Appendix C – Thermal Management System: Detailed Design

C.1 Battery Immersion Cooling (Passive)

Fluid: Novec 7500 (3M) – dielectric, boiling point 128 °C, thermal conductivity 0.065 W/m·K, specific heat 1128 J/kg·K, density 1610 kg/m³.

Configuration:

· Fluid occupies 15 % of free volume within pack (≈ 4.5 L).
· Cells arranged vertically; fluid fills lower 30 mm.
· Natural convection: buoyancy‑driven flow through cell gaps.
· Heat transfer coefficient (empirical correlation for vertical cylinder arrays): h \approx 150\ \text{W/m}^2\text{K} at ΔT = 10 K.

Heat rejection path:

· Heat conducted through cell sidewall → fluid → battery sidewall (Al 2 mm) → ambient air.
· Sidewall radiator: vertical fins (extruded Al 6061‑T6), fin pitch 5 mm, height 40 mm, length 1400 mm, total surface area 0.8 m².
· Natural convection to ambient: h_{\text{air}} \approx 8\ \text{W/m}^2\text{K} (still air), up to 20 W/m²·K with ram air.
· Total thermal resistance cell‑to‑ambient: R_{\text{th}} \approx 0.45\ \text{K/W} per cell string.

Steady‑state temperature rise:

\Delta T = P \cdot R_{\text{th}}

At 800 W continuous heat load, ΔT = 800 × 0.45 = 360 K → not sustainable. Therefore:

· Continuous heat load limited to 800 W by limiting discharge current to ≤ 0.5 C (≈ 20 kW).
· Peak loads (acceleration) handled by thermal capacitance: pack mass 240 kg, specific heat 900 J/kg·K → ΔT ≈ 3 K per 100 kW·s.

Active liquid cooling variant:

· External coolant loop (water‑glycol, 25 %).
· Electric pump (48 V, 200 W, 10 L/min).
· Front‑mounted radiator (400 × 300 × 40 mm), forced air.
· Heat rejection capacity: 3 kW at ΔT = 20 K (coolant‑to‑ambient).
· Enables 1 C continuous discharge (38 kW).

C.2 Motor/Inverter Thermosiphon Oil Cooling

Oil: Shell E‑fluid E6+, thermal conductivity 0.15 W/m·K, specific heat 2000 J/kg·K, viscosity 32 cSt @40 °C.

Circuit:

· Oil sump integrated in motor housing (0.8 L).
· Electric pump (48 V, 20 W, 2 L/min) activates when inverter temperature > 70 °C.
· Oil flows through stator cooling channels (spiral, 6 mm diameter), exits to external radiator.

Radiator:

· Aluminium, 300 × 200 × 40 mm, louvered fins, 15 rows.
· Natural convection + ram air: heat rejection capacity P_{\text{rad}} = 1.5\ \text{kW} at ΔT = 40 K (air‑to‑oil).
· Mounted under rear floor, exposed to ram air when vehicle moves.

Thermal equilibrium:

· Motor loss at 35 kW output: P_{\text{loss}} = P_{\text{elec}} (1 - \eta_{\text{motor}}) = 35 \cdot (1 - 0.94) \approx 2.1\ \text{kW}.
· Radiator rejection at ΔT = 35 K: 1.5 \cdot (35/40) = 1.31\ \text{kW}.
· Deficit: 0.79 kW absorbed by thermal capacitance of rear subframe (22 kg Al, C_p = 900 J/kg·K) → temperature rise 0.04 K/s → after 10 min, ΔT ≈ 24 K → equilibrium reached at ~95 °C.

---

Appendix D – Electrical and Electronics Architecture Schematics

D.1 Power Distribution Diagram

```
HV Battery (355V, 38.4 kWh) ─┬─ HV Contactors (pre‑charge) ── Inverter ── Motor
                              └─ HV PTC Heater (4 kW) ── Cabin
48V DC/DC (3 kW) ── 48V Bus ── Zone Controllers ── Lights, Pumps, Fans, ZCU
12V DC/DC (300 W) ── 12V Bus ── HMI, CAN transceivers, BMS keep‑alive
```

D.2 Zonal Controller Functional Allocation

Zone Controller Loads Communication Safety Integrity
Front ZCU‑F Headlamps (LED), DRL, wiper, steering torque sensor, frunk latch, coolant pump CAN FD (chassis) ASIL‑B (steering torque)
Rear ZCU‑R Taillamps, charge port lock, inverter enable, reverse lamp, charge indicator CAN FD (powertrain) ASIL‑B (inverter enable)
Cabin ZCU‑C HVAC blower, PTC relay, seat motors, infotainment display, UI, BMS HMI Ethernet (100BASE‑T1) QM

Ethernet backbone: Single twisted pair, shielded, length 5 m, routed along battery perimeter.
CAN FD bus: Dual redundant for powertrain; single for chassis.

D.3 Battery Management System (BMS) Architecture

· Distributed cell monitoring: 10 daisy‑chains, each monitoring 12 cells (LTC6813 or equivalent).
· Master BMS located in battery enclosure, isolated CAN to vehicle.
· Passive balancing: 100 mA bleed current.
· Contactor control logic:
  · Pre‑charge circuit via 100 Ω resistor, 5 A rated.
  · Welding detection: voltage sense across contactor after open command.
· Isolation monitoring: Continuous measurement of HV‑to‑chassis resistance; threshold 500 Ω/V, shutdown if <100 Ω/V.
· Cybersecurity: Secure boot, signed firmware updates, CAN authentication (optional).

